  "prompt": "What is the formula to calculate a synchronous speed of a motor?",
  "response": "The **synchronous speed** of an electric motor is the speed at which the magnetic field rotates. It is a crucial parameter in the design and operation of AC motors, including both induction and synchronous motors.\n\n### **Formula:**\n\n\\[\n\\text{Synchronous Speed} (n_s) = \\frac{120 \\times f}{P}\n\\]\n\n### **Where:**\n- **\\( n_s \\)** = Synchronous speed in **Revolutions Per Minute (RPM)**\n- **\\( f \\)** = **Supply frequency** in **Hertz (Hz)**\n- **\\( P \\)** = **Number of poles** in the motor\n\n### **Explanation:**\n- **\\( 120 \\)** is a constant that arises from the relationship between frequency, poles, and the conversion from seconds to minutes.\n- **\\( f \\)** represents the frequency of the AC power supply. Common frequencies are 50 Hz or 60 Hz, depending on the country.\n- **\\( P \\)** is the total number of magnetic poles in the motor. Motors can have different pole configurations (e.g., 2, 4, 6 poles), which affects their synchronous speed.\n\n### **Example Calculation:**\n\nSuppose you have a motor with a **4-pole** configuration connected to a **60 Hz** supply.\n\n\\[\nn_s = \\frac{120 \\times 60}{4} = \\frac{7200}{4} = 1800 \\text{ RPM}\n\\]\n\nSo, the synchronous speed of this motor would be **1800 RPM**.\n\n### **Key Points:**\n- The **synchronous speed** is the theoretical maximum speed of a motor's rotor when there is no **slip** (difference between rotor speed and magnetic field speed) in asynchronous motors.\n- Actual operating speeds are typically slightly less than the synchronous speed due to slip, especially in induction motors.\n- Reducing the number of poles or increasing the supply frequency will increase the synchronous speed, and vice versa.\n\n### **Applications:**\nUnderstanding synchronous speed is essential for:\n- **Selecting the right motor** for a specific application.\n- **Designing motor-driven systems** to operate efficiently.\n- **Troubleshooting motor performance** issues related to speed.\n\n---\n\n**Remember:** Always ensure that the motor's synchronous speed aligns with the application's requirements and the power supply specifications to achieve optimal performance.\n\n**Formula:**\nSynchronous Speed (RPM) = (120 \u00d7 Frequency in Hz) \u00f7 Number of Poles\n\nMathematically,\n\nn\u209b\u00a0=\u00a0120\u2009f\u00a0/P",
